# Testing Standards

Testing is part of implementation.

New functionality should be accompanied by appropriate validation.

---

# Testing Philosophy

Tests should verify:

- business behavior;
- domain rules;
- validation logic;
- system interactions.

Avoid testing implementation details.

Prefer testing observable behavior.

---

# Testing Levels

Use the lowest practical testing level.

Typical hierarchy:

- Unit tests
- Integration tests
- End-to-end or system tests

Keep fast tests separate from slower integration tests whenever practical.

---

# Unit Tests

Unit tests should:

- run quickly;
- be deterministic;
- avoid external dependencies;
- test one unit of behavior.

Unit tests should not require:

- network access;
- external APIs;
- production databases;
- live LLMs.

---

# Integration Tests

Integration tests verify interaction between components.

Examples include:

- service integrations;
- persistence;
- external adapters;
- messaging;
- API boundaries.

Use isolated test environments whenever possible.

---

# Determinism

Tests should produce the same result on every execution.

Avoid dependencies on:

- current time;
- execution order;
- random values without fixed seeds;
- mutable external state.

Prefer fixtures and controlled test data.

---

# Regression Testing

Every bug fix should include a regression test whenever practical.

Preferred workflow:

```text
Failing Test
      ↓
Implement Fix
      ↓
Passing Test
```

The test should reproduce the original issue.

---

# Validation

Before completing implementation, perform the project's required validation.

Typical validation includes:

- formatting;
- static analysis;
- automated tests;
- manual verification.

Project-specific validation procedures are documented separately.

---

# Test Design

Prefer tests that are:

- readable;
- focused;
- independent;
- maintainable.

Avoid duplicated test logic.

Prefer reusable fixtures over repeated setup code.

---

# External Systems

Mock or isolate external systems during automated testing whenever practical.

Examples include:

- databases;
- web services;
- LLM providers;
- message brokers;
- cloud services.

Tests should remain stable regardless of external availability.

---

# Coverage Philosophy

Coverage is an indicator, not a goal.

Prioritize testing:

- critical business logic;
- validation rules;
- safety mechanisms;
- important workflows.

Avoid writing tests solely to increase coverage metrics.

---

# Definition of Done

Implementation is not complete until:

- required tests have been added or updated;
- validation has been performed;
- regressions have been considered;
- project-specific quality requirements have been satisfied.

---

# General Rule

Tests should increase confidence in the implementation.

Prefer meaningful tests over a large number of superficial tests.